---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const readingPath = [
  { label: 'Overview', href: '/overview/' },
  { label: 'Start here', href: '/start-here/' },
  { label: 'Claims matrix', href: '/docs/current/claims-matrix/' },
  { label: 'Literature review', href: '/docs/established/literature-review/' },
];
---
<BaseLayout title="Overview" description="A plain-language introduction to HELIOS-3D.">
  <header class="mb-12 pb-6 border-b border-obsidian-3">
    <p class="text-xs font-mono uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-amber mb-3">Public overview</p>
    <h1 class="text-5xl font-bold text-amber mb-4">What HELIOS-3D is, and is not</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-parchment-2 max-w-3xl leading-relaxed">
      HELIOS-3D is a research site about a speculative spintronic computing
      program. It asks whether magnetic textures such as hopfions could one day
      support more energy-efficient computation, but it does not claim a working
      device today.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-3 mb-12">
    <article class="rounded-lg border border-obsidian-3 bg-obsidian-2 p-6">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-amber mb-3">Why it exists</h2>
      <p class="text-parchment-2 leading-relaxed">
        Modern computing moves a lot of charge, and moving charge costs energy.
        HELIOS-3D explores whether topological spin textures could reduce some of
        that cost.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="rounded-lg border border-obsidian-3 bg-obsidian-2 p-6">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-amber mb-3">What it studies</h2>
      <p class="text-parchment-2 leading-relaxed">
        The project follows a staged research path: established physics,
        candidate materials, current evidence, and long-range speculation.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="rounded-lg border border-obsidian-3 bg-obsidian-2 p-6">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-amber mb-3">What it does not claim</h2>
      <p class="text-parchment-2 leading-relaxed">
        The site does not present a finished chip or a proven sub-Landauer
        computer. It keeps the line between evidence, inference, and speculation
        visible.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="rounded-xl border border-ember/25 bg-ember/5 p-6 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-amber mb-3">How to read the site</h2>
    <p class="text-parchment-2 leading-relaxed mb-5 max-w-3xl">
      Start here if you want the big picture. Then move into the guided path,
      the claims matrix, and the literature review. That order gives you context
      before detail.
    </p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      {readingPath.map((item) => (
        <a href={item.href} class="rounded-full border border-obsidian-3 px-4 py-2 text-sm text-parchment-2 hover:border-amber hover:text-amber transition-colors">
          {item.label}
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
    <article class="rounded-lg border border-obsidian-3 bg-obsidian-2 p-6">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-amber mb-3">The public version</h2>
      <p class="text-parchment-2 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        If you are new to the topic, read this page first and then use the
        guided path. It gives you a short explanation before you meet the more
        technical language.
      </p>
      <a href="/start-here/" class="text-amber hover:underline">Open the guided path →</a>
    </article>

    <article class="rounded-lg border border-obsidian-3 bg-obsidian-2 p-6">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-amber mb-3">The technical trail</h2>
      <p class="text-parchment-2 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        If you want the evidence first, jump straight to the claims matrix and
        literature review.
      </p>
      <a href="/docs/current/claims-matrix/" class="text-amber hover:underline">Open the claims matrix →</a>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
